{"id":"project-LICHEN-x1h3","title":"Data race in tx_queue_count and tx_queue_empty","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/link/tx_queue.c
Lines: 311-341

tx_queue_count() and tx_queue_empty() read queue->entries[i].valid without holding the queue lock:

```c
int tx_queue_count(const struct tx_queue *queue)
{
    // ... no lock_queue(queue) call
    for (int i = 0; i < TX_QUEUE_SIZE; i++) {
        if (queue->entries[i].valid) {  // Data race
            count++;
        }
    }
    return count;
}
```

Similarly for tx_queue_empty() at lines 328-341.

While individual bool reads may be atomic on most architectures, the iteration over multiple entries without synchronization can yield inconsistent results - e.g., counting an entry that was just invalidated while missing one that was just added.

Impact: Inconsistent queue state reporting in concurrent scenarios. May affect backpressure decisions if callers rely on accurate counts.

Fix: Acquire lock before iteration, or document that these functions provide approximate values only (the stats read already has such documentation).","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:46:59.704661Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:46:59.704689Z"}
